{{infobox organization | name = Selden Society | image = Selden Soc vols.jpg | image_border = | size = 300 | map = | msize = | mcaption = | alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] --> | caption = Selden Society volumes | formation = [[1887]] | type = [[Learned society]] | status = [[charitable organization|Charity]] | registration_id = 211536 | purpose = Historical and Legal Study and Research | headquarters = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]] | leader_title = Activities | leader_name = Research & Publications, Lectures & Events | leader_title2 = Collections | leader_name2 = Library, Archives | leader_title3 = Patron | leader_name3 = [[Prince_Philip,_Duke_of_Edinburgh|H.R.H. The Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]] | leader_title4 = President | leader_name4 = Nicholas Le Poidevin QC | website = [https://www.seldensociety.ac.uk/ www.seldensociety.ac.uk] }}
'''The Selden Society''' is a [[learned society]] and [[registered charity]] concerned with the study of [[English legal history]]. It functions primarily as a [[text publication society]], but also undertakes other activities to promote scholarship within its sphere of interest. It is the only learned society wholly devoted to the topic of English legal history.
The Society takes its name from the eminent English jurist and legal and constitutional scholar, [[John Selden]] (1584–1654).
==History and activities== The Society was founded in 1887 by [[Frederic William Maitland|F. W. Maitland]]. Its principal activity is publishing historical records of [[English law]]. Since its inception, a volume of significant texts has been published every year. It also publishes a supplementary series.
The President is Professor Sir [[John Baker (legal historian)|John Baker]], former [[Downing Professor of the Laws of England]] at [[Cambridge University]]. The current literary director is Dr [[Neil Jones (academic)|Neil Jones]], who succeeded Sir John Baker in this role in 2011. The Secretary is [[Victor Tunkel]]. The Society meets for an AGM every year, and other meetings are held in the [[United States]] and [[Australia]]. The Society often collaborates with the [[Ames Foundation]] at [[Harvard Law School]].
The membership of the Society is primarily composed of educational institutions and interested individuals (mostly legal historians and lawyers).
==Publications== Early volumes published by the Society included:
*{{cite book |editor-last=Maitland |editor-first=F. W. |editor-link=Frederic William Maitland |title=Select Pleas of the Crown. Vol. I: A.D. 1200–1225 |series=Selden Society Publications |volume=1 |year=1888 }} *{{cite book |editor-last=Maitland |editor-first=F. W. |editor-link=Frederic William Maitland|title=Select Pleas in Manorial and other Seignorial Courts. Vol. I: Reigns of Henry III and Edward I |series=Selden Society Publications |volume=2 |year=1889 }} *{{cite book |editor-last=Paley Baildon |editor-first=William |title=Select Civil Pleas. Vol. I: A.D. 1200–1203 |series=Selden Society Publications |volume=3 |year=1890 }} ::This volume made use of [[record type]], in an attempt to present the text in a near [[facsimile]] of the original manuscript sources. F. W. Maitland expressed reservations about the experiment, and it was not repeated.<ref>Yale and Baker 1987, pp, 22, 34.</ref> *{{cite book |editor1-last=Maitland |editor1-first=F. W. |editor1-link=Frederic William Maitland |editor2-last=Paley Baildon |editor2-first=William |title=The Court Baron; being precedents for use in seignorial and other courts, together with select pleas from the Bishop of Ely's Court at Littleport |series=Selden Society Publications |volume=4 |year=1891 }} *{{cite book |editor-last=Hudson |editor-first=W. |title=Leet Jurisdiction in the City of Norwich during the 13th and 14th centuries, with a short notice of its later history and decline, from rolls in the possession of the corporation |series=Selden Society Publications |volume=5 |year=1892 }}
Volumes published in recent years include:
*{{cite book |editor-last=Brand |editor-first=Paul A. |title=The Earliest English Law Reports. Vol. III: Eyre reports to 1285| series=Selden Society Publications |volume=122 |year=2006 }} *{{cite book |editor-last=Brand |editor-first=Paul A. |title=The Earliest English Law Reports. Vol. IV: Eyre reports to 1286 and undated Eyre reports; Exchequer of the Jews reports; Pre-1290 Assize reports; Pre-1290 Reports from unidentified courts and additional pre-1290 Common Bench reports |series=Selden Society Publications |volume=123 |year=2006 }} *{{cite book |editor-last=Baker |editor-first=Sir John |editor-link=John Baker (legal historian) |title=The Reports of William Dalison, 1552–1558 |series=Selden Society Publications |volume=124 |year=2007 }} *{{cite book |editor-last=Lyall |editor-first=Andrew |title=Irish Exchequer Reports. Reports of cases in the Courts of Exchequer and Chancery in Ireland, 1716–1734 |series=Selden Society Publications |volume=125 |year=2009 }} *{{cite book |editor-last=Helmholz |editor-first=R. H. |editor-link=Richard H. Helmholz |title=Three Civilian Notebooks, 1580–1640 |series=Selden Society Publications |volume=127 |year=2011 }} *{{cite book |editor-last=Oldham |editor-first=James |title=Case Notes of Sir Souldern Lawrence, 1787–1800 |series=Selden Society Publications |volume=128 |year=2013 }} *{{cite book |editor-last=Baker |editor-first=Sir John |editor-link=John Baker (legal historian) |title=Selected Readings and Commentaries on Magna Carta, 1400–1604 |series=Selden Society Publications |volume=132 |year=2015 }} *{{cite book |editor-last=McGlynn |editor-first=Margaret |title=The Rights and Liberties of the English Church: Readings from the Prereformation Inns of Court |series=Selden Society Publications |volume=129 |year=2016 }} *{{cite book |editor1-last=Bonfield |editor1-first=Lloyd |editor2-last=Poos |editor2-first=L. R. |title=Reports of Sir Peter King, Chief Justice of the Common Pleas, 1714–22 |series=Selden Society Publications |volume=130 |year=2017 }}
==Yale Prize== The David Yale Prize is awarded biennially to a young scholar (under the age of 35) for a distinguished contribution to the laws and legal institutions of England and Wales. The award was set up in 1999 in honour of David Yale [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]] Hon [[Queen's Counsel|Q.C.]], former President of the Selden Society. The prize has been awarded to:
*1999 Thomas P. Gallanis for his article "The Rise of Modern Evidence Law" *2001 Daniel Klerman for his article "Settlement and the Decline of Private Prosecution in Thirteenth-Century England" *2003 Neil Jones for his article "The Use Upon a Use in Equity Revisited" *2007 Sara Elin Roberts for her monograph ''The Legal Triads of Medieval Wales'' *2013 Ian Williams *2017 Kenneth F. Duggan for his article "The Hue and Cry in Thirteenth-Century England"
