{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}} {{Use British English|date=August 2015}} {{Infobox Historic Site | name = The Oratory| native_name = | image = Oratory-St-James.jpg| image_size = 250| caption = The Oratory| locmapin = United Kingdom Liverpool Central| map_width = 200| map_caption = Location in Liverpool| alt = | coordinates = {{coord|53.3988|-2.9732|display=inline,title}} | location = [[Liverpool]], [[Merseyside]], England| gbgridref = SJ 354 895| area = | elevation = | formed = | founded = | built = 1829| built_for = | demolished = | rebuilt = | restored = | restored_by = | architect = [[John Foster (architect)|John Foster]]| architecture = [[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival]]| visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = [[National Museums Liverpool]]| designation1 = Grade I| designation1_offname = | designation1_type = | designation1_criteria = | designation1_date = 28&nbsp;June 1952| delisted1_date = | designation1_parent = | designation1_number = 1063282| designation1_free1name = | designation1_free1value = | designation1_free2name = | designation1_free2value = | designation1_free3name = | designation1_free3value = | designation2 = | designation2_offname = | designation2_type = | designation2_criteria = | designation2_date = | delisted2_date = | designation2_parent = | designation2_number = | designation2_free1name = | designation2_free1value = | designation2_free2name = | designation2_free2value = | designation2_free3name = | designation2_free3value = }}
'''The Oratory''' stands to the north of [[Liverpool Cathedral]] in [[Merseyside]], England. It was originally the mortuary chapel to [[St James Cemetery]], and houses a collection of 19th-century sculpture and important funeral monuments as part of the [[Walker Art Gallery]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Oratory|url=http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/walker/about/oratory/index.aspx|publisher=Walker Art Gallery|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> It is a [[Listed building#Categories of listed building|Grade&nbsp;I listed building]] in the [[National Heritage List for England]].
==History== The Oratory was built in 1829, and used for funeral services before burials in the adjacent cemetery. It was designed by [[John Foster (architect)|John Foster]]. When the cemetery closed, the building fell into disuse. In 1986 it came under the care of [[National Museums Liverpool]], and is used to contain a collection of sculpture and statues.<ref>{{Citation | last = Pye| first = Ken| author-link = | publication-date = | date = | year = 2011| title = Discover Liverpool| edition = | volume = | series = | publication-place = Liverpool| place = | publisher = Trinity Mirror Media| pages = | page = 50| format = | id = | isbn = 978-1-906802-90-5| doi = | oclc = | url = | accessdate =}}</ref>
==Architecture== The building is in the form of a Greek [[Doric order|Doric]] temple. At each end is a [[portico]] with six columns. There are no windows and the building is lit from above. Inside, a [[coffer]]ed ceiling is supported by [[Ionic order|Ionic]] columns. Pollard and [[Nikolaus Pevsner|Pevsner]] consider this to be Foster's best surviving building.<ref name=pev>{{Citation | last = Sharples | first = Joseph| author-link = | last2 = Pollard| first2 = Richard| author2-link = | publication-date = | date = | year = 2004| title = Liverpool| edition = | volume = | series = Pevsner Architectural Guides| publication-place = New Haven and London| place = | publisher = [[Yale University Press]]| pages = 243–244| page = | format = | id = | isbn = 0-300-10258-5| doi = | oclc = | url = | accessdate =}}</ref> On 28&nbsp;June 1952 it was designated as a Grade&nbsp;I listed building.<ref name=nhl>{{NHLE |num= 1063282|desc= The Oratory, Liverpool |grade= I |accessdate= 19 August 2012 |mode=cs2 |ps=none}}</ref> In the National Heritage List for England it is described as "one of the purest monuments of the Greek Revival in England".<ref name=nhl/> Around the Oratory are [[cast iron]] railings and gate [[pier (architecture)|piers]] that have been listed at Grade&nbsp;II.<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1359856 |desc= Railing and Piers to The Oratory, Liverpool |grade= II |accessdate= 19 August 2012 |mode=cs2 |ps=none |fewer-links=x}}</ref>
==Collection== Inside the building is a collection of monuments, mainly [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]] [[relief]]s, many of which were brought here from demolished buildings in the 1980s. These include a monument dated 1834 to the Nicholson family by [[Francis Leggatt Chantrey|Francis Chantrey]], one to William Earle, who died in 1839, by [[John Gibson (sculptor)|John Gibson]], to Dr William Stevenson, who died in 1853, by J. A. P. Macbride, to William Hammerton, who died in 1832, by Gibson, to William Ewart, who died in 1823, by Joseph Gott, to Emily Robinson, who died in 1829, by Gibson, and to [[Agnes Jones]], who died in 1868, by [[Pietro Tenerani]].<ref name=pev/> There is also a statue of [[William Huskisson]] by Gibson that was formerly in the Custom House.<ref name=nhl/>
